<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP ALBUM CHART; J.M. MONTGOMERY'S 'KICKIN' IT UP' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DENNIS HUNT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Country singer John Michael Montgomery has been the target of some nasty 
critical cracks--like being dubbed Billy Ray Cyrus II, the country hunk, 
flash-in-the-pan, etc. So with "Kickin' It Up" reaching the top of the pop 
album chart in just two weeks, he must be kickin' up his heels with joy--and 
thumbing his nose at all those detractors. Even after the album entered at No. 
3 last week, many were predicting it would sink quickly out of the Top 10. That 
loud noise you hear is those detractors eating crow. NKOTB, alias New Kids on 
the Block, must be singing the blues about its new album, "Face the Music." 
After debuting at No. 37 last week, it dropped to No. 75. One theory is that 
they distanced themselves so much from their old teen-idol image that their 
hard-core fans don't know they have a new album. Another theory is that judging 
from the scathing reviews, it's simply a bad album fans don't care about. 
Celine Dion's "The Power of Love" is still the No. 1 pop single. 04,53,06,08,08 
Rank Rank 2 Weeks Last Weeks on the Week Ago Chart 1. "Kickin' It Up," John 
Michael Montgomery 3 ... 2 2. "Music Box," Mariah Carey 2 1 23 3. "Doggystyle," 
Snoop Doggy Dogg 4 2 11 4. "Jar of Flies," Alice in Chains 1 ... 2 5. "12 
Play," R. Kelly 9 12 13 6. "Very Necessary," Salt-N-Pepa 7 10 17 7. "Toni 
Braxton," Toni Braxton 10 11 30 8. "Diary of a Mad Band," Jodeci 6 3 7 9. 
"Greatest Hits," Tom Petty 5 5 12 10. "August and Everything After," Counting 
Crows 15 13 8 * "Under the Pink," Tori Amos ... ... 1 * Singer Tori Amos' cult 
following seems to have grown considerably. With her new album entering the 
chart at No. 12, she's on the brink of becoming a full-fledged, mainstream pop 
star. 
</P>
