<HEADLINE>
<P>
MUSIC REVIEW; SOME HIGHS AND LOWS WITH MOSCOW VIRTUOSI IN CERRITOS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DANIEL CARIAGA, TIMES MUSIC WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Still on the road, still all-male, still often living up to its immodest name, 
the Moscow Virtuosi remains a viable musical ensemble worthy of its good 
reputation. Vladimir Spivakov leads the group he founded 15 years ago; these 
days, its headquarters is not the capital of Russia, but the Northwest region 
of Spain: Asturias. 
</P>
<P>
 Between East Coast and Northern California dates this week, the 22-member 
orchestra stopped in Southern California for a single concert at the Cerritos 
Center for the Performing Arts -- and reminded veteran watchers that when it is 
alert, it plays wonderfully well, but when it is not interested, its 
performances can become boring. 
</P>
<P>
 Both kinds of playing characterized its Wednesday night concert at the 
Cerritos showplace, arranged on this occasion in that configuration, which 
holds 960 listeners. There was a Mozart symphony, two concertos by Haydn and 
Shostakovich's Chamber Symphony in F -- a generous program not truly engaging 
until its last half-hour. 
</P>
<P>
 That was the orchestral version of Shostakovich's Third String Quartet, a work 
that begins in empty-headedness and ends in poignancy, having passed by that 
time through melancholy, irony and bitterness. The performance emerged 
emotionally pointed, perfectly gauged dynamically and texturally transparent. 
</P>
<P>
 All members seemed to participate in the success and integration of this 
reading, but two soloists in particular contributed most strongly: 
concertmaster Arkady Futer and principal cellist Mikhail Milman. 
</P>
<P>
 What preceded this programmatic climax was a series of incomplete starts: 
Mozart's Symphony No. 29 in a dutiful run-through clearly unconnected with its 
true greatness; Haydn's C-major Cello Concerto, a fine showcase for the 
unfolding talents of the 20-year-old American soloist, Wendy Warner, and 
Haydn's C-major Violin Concerto, in which Spivakov again revealed his steely 
brilliant technique, tight control and abundant skills as a fiddler. 
</P>
<P>
 The orchestra mustered a mediocre accompaniment for the guest soloist, a more 
careful musical collaboration with its violinist-leader. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Concert Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
