<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY: THE ECONOMY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Money Supply Falls: The two broadest measures of the nation's money supply 
fell in the week ended Jan. 31, the Federal Reserve Board reported. The Fed 
said the measure known as M2 fell to a seasonally adjusted $3,568.4 billion 
from a revised $3,573.3 billion the previous week.An even broader measure, M3, 
fell to a seasonally adjusted $4,224.8 billion from a revised $4,230.7 billion. 
The narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, rose to a seasonally adjusted 
$1,136.5 billion from $1,136.4 billion. M1 includes cash in circulation, 
deposits in checking accounts and non-bank traveler's checks. M2 is M1 plus 
accounts such as savings deposits and money market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus 
less-liquid accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations 
of $100,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
