<HEADLINE>
<P>
BEHIND THE SCENES: FASHION; CLOTHES MAKE THE MAN A LOSER IN THE DATING GAME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sighs of disappointment were heard at "Let's Make a Date," a fund-raiser at 
Trattoria Spiga in Costa Mesa that tried to find matches between women from the 
Cystic Fibrosis Foundation and men from Young Professionals Against Cancer. 
</P>
<P>
 The simulated "Studs" game show Tuesday should have been called "Duds."  
</P>
<P>
 The heartbreaking outcome?  
</P>
<P>
 None of the three women, each of whom went out with the two men, chose to have 
another date with destiny. 
</P>
<P>
 Were the guys rejected because their standard-cut suits were as sartorially 
exciting as dating a sibling? No. The turnoff, said the women, was that the 
men's clothes reflected their conservative personalities.  
</P>
<P>
 "There was no sparkle," sniffed a disapproving woman contestant. "And they 
looked like George Bush." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
